  "dcterms:abstract": "Huntington's disease (HD) is the result of expression of a mutated Huntingtin protein (mHtt), which is associated with a variety of cellular dysfunctions, including excessive mitochondrial fission. Here, we tested whether inhibition of excessive mitochondrial fission prevents mHtt-induced pathology. We developed a selective inhibitor (P110-TAT) of the mitochondrial fission protein dynamin-related protein 1 (Drp1). P110-TAT treatment inhibited mHtt-induced excessive mitochondrial fragmentation, improved mitochondrial function, and increased cell viability in HD cell culture models.",
  "schema:datePublished": "2013-12-01",
  "schema:keywords": [
    "Huntington's disease",
    "Mitochondrial fragmentation",
    "Neurodegeneration",
    "Drp1 inhibition",
    "Cell viability"
  ],
  "fabio:hasPublicationVenue": {
    "@id": "https://doi.org/10.1172/JCI",
    "@type": "fabio:Journal",
    "schema:name": "The Journal of Clinical Investigation"
  },
  "fabio:hasPart": [
    {
      "@id": "sec1",
      "@type": "fabio:Section",
      "dcterms:title": "Introduction",
      "fabio:hasContent": "Huntington's disease (HD) is a neurodegenerative disorder characterized by a variety of cellular dysfunctions, including excessive mitochondrial fission."
    },
    {
      "@id": "sec2",
      "@type": "fabio:Section",
      "dcterms:title": "Methods",
      "fabio:hasContent": "We developed a selective peptide inhibitor, P110-TAT, to target the Drp1 protein to test its effects on mitochondrial fission in HD models."
    },
    {
      "@id": "sec3",
      "@type": "fabio:Section",
      "dcterms:title": "Results",
      "fabio:hasContent": "P110-TAT inhibited excessive mitochondrial fragmentation in HD models, leading to improved mitochondrial function and increased cell viability."
    },
    {
      "@id": "sec4",
      "@type": "fabio:Section",
      "dcterms:title": "Discussion",
      "fabio:hasContent": "The inhibition of Drp1-dependent mitochondrial fission with P110-TAT-like inhibitors may prevent or slow the progression of HD."
    }
  ],
